                News            


Koury, decrying numbers, wants bank to find exit




Oct 15, 2007, 12:00am EDT



Updated Oct 11, 2007, 4:43pm EDT











Lee Weisbecker












Lee Weisbecker


 


 







                    Share
                


























 Order Reprints


 Save Article




 Print





 










 



 Email




 Facebook




 LinkedIn




 Twitter




 Save Article





More 






 Email




 Facebook




 LinkedIn




 Twitter




 Save Article



























Lee Weisbecker






 











BURLINGTON - Maurice J. Koury, a benefactor to the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and a serial investor in North Carolina banks, has fired off a letter to the managers of Wilmington's Cape Fear Bank, telling them it's time to give investors an exit.
"I write to you today to express my dissatisfaction with your stewardship of Cape Fear Bank Corporation," Koury writes in the Sept. 26 letter to CEO John Cameron Coburn and other officials of the publicly traded bank.





 


In nine years, Koury says, shareholders have seen a 43 percent return on their investment, based on the bank's Sept. 14 close of $9.10 a share, even as the CEO's base salary, before bonus and options, rose by 385 percent, to $250,000.
"I cannot understand increasing the compensation and benefits ... while the shareholders of the company continue to receive no dividends and watch our stock price decline," Koury writes. "I believe that it is time for the company to retain a qualified financial advisor to explore the company's strategic alternatives to maximize shareholder value, including a sale."
Koury included a copy of his letter in a U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission filing that reports his stock holdings in Cape Fear. Those filings show that he has purchased more than 21,000 shares in the bank since late July and currently owns a total of 189,620 shares, or 5 percent of Cape Fear stock.
Coburn, asked for a response, confirmed he had received Koury's letter. "I always welcome comment from shareholders," Coburn says. "Our board will consider it thoroughly and comment at the appropriate time."
As for Cape Fear's financial performance, he adds, "We have a long-term plan for success that we believe will create results for our shareholders."
From its opening in June 1998 until October 2006, Cape Fear was known as the Bank of Wilmington. The name change was made to emphasize the institution's new commitment to counties - Brunswick and Pender - in the lower Cape Fear River region. The headquarters remains in Wilmington, in New Hanover County.





 


As of June 30, the bank had seven offices in the three counties, a staff of 99 and total assets of $441 million, according to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
Return on equity - a number that reveals how much profit a bank is generating with shareholder commitments - dropped from 8 percent to 6.8 percent for the 12 months ending June 30, according to the FDIC. A median bank ROE is considered 10.22 percent, while superior is 12.30 percent and higher.
A native of Burlington who was born in 1929, Koury owns Carolina Hosiery Mills Inc., has developed hotels and served as a member of the UNC Board of Trustees. His fundraising efforts on behalf of UNC helped get the Dean E. Smith Center and the school's George Watts Hill Alumni Center off the ground.
He was a 10 percent stakeholder in Burlington's 1st State Bank, which was acquired by Raleigh's Capital Bank in early 2006.
In 2005, Koury was a vocal and public opponent of Smithfield-based KS Bank's plan to go private to avoid higher accounting costs. In the mind of Koury, who later accepted a buyout offer from KS managers, the plan would have limited shareholder transparency into bank performance.
"He's a man who says what he thinks," says Koury spokesman Milt Petty, adding that Koury wouldn't be taking follow-up questions regarding Cape Fear. "He said everything he has to say in the letter."







 





 















































 






















